{"cursor":"5320","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\nAn 'optical flat' is an optical-grade piece of glass lapped and polished to be\nextremely flat on one or both sides, usually within a few millionths of an inch\n(about 25 nanometres). They are used with a monochromatic light to determine the\nflatness of other optical surfaces by interference. {{cite book\n|last=English\n| first= R. E.\n|editor-first=Albert G.\n| editor-last=Ingalls\n|editor-link=Albert Graham Ingalls |title=Amateur Telescope Making, Book Three\n|publisher=Scientific American |year=1953 |pages=156â162 |chapter=Optical Flats\n|isbn=}} When an optical flat is placed on another surface and\nilluminated, the light waves reflect off both the bottom surface of the flat and\nthe surface it is resting on. The reflected waves interfere, creating a pattern\nof interference fringes (Newton's rings), visible as light and dark bands. The\nspacing between the fringes is smaller where the gap is changing more rapidly,\nindicating a departure from flatness in one of the two surfaces, in a similar\nway to the contour lines on a map. A flat surface is indicated by a pattern of\nstraight, parallel fringes with equal spacing, while other patterns indicate\nuneven surfaces. Two adjacent fringes indicate a difference in elevation of one-\nhalf wavelength of the light used, so by counting the fringes differences in\nelevation of the surface can be measured to millionths of an inch.\n\nUsually only one of the two surfaces is made optically flat to the specified\ntolerance, and this surface is indicated by an arrow on the edge of the glass.\n\nOptical flats are sometimes given an optical coating and used as precision\nmirrors for special purposes, such as in a FabryâPÃ©rot interferometer or laser\ncavity. Optical flats have uses in spectrophotometry as well.\n","linknr":125,"url":"Optical_flat","recorded":1374780784,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Optical_flat&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Optical_flat&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cext.uls.nojs%7Cmediawiki.legacy.commonPrint%2Cshared%7Cmw.PopUpMediaTransform%7Cskins.vector&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=site&only=styles&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=startup&only=scripts&skin=vector&*","//bits.wikimedia.org/geoiplookup","//meta.wikimedia.org","#mw-navigation","#p-search","/wiki/File:OpticalFlats157-03.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/1/10/OpticalFlats157-03.jpg/220px-OpticalFlats157-03.jpg","/wiki/File:OpticalFlats157-03.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/File:Optical_flat_interference_fringes.jpg","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Optical_flat_interference_fringes.jpg/220px-Optical_flat_interference_fringes.jpg","/wiki/File:Optical_flat_interference_fringes.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.22wmf8/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","/wiki/Glass","/wiki/Lapping","/wiki/Polishing","/wiki/Monochromatic_light","/wiki/Interference_(wave_propagation)","#cite_note-1","/wiki/Interference_fringe","/wiki/Newton%27s_rings","/wiki/Wavelength","/wiki/Optical_coating","/wiki/Mirror","/wiki/Fabry%E2%80%93P%C3%A9rot_interferometer","/wiki/Laser_cavity","/wiki/Spectrophotometry","#Physical_Stability","#How_interference_fringes_form","#See_also","#References","/w/index.php?title=Optical_flat&action=edit&section=1","#cite_note-2","/w/index.php?title=Optical_flat&action=edit&section=2","/wiki/File:Optical_flat_interference.svg","//upload.wikimedia